To find the value of $k$ that makes the line $-\frac{1}{2}-2kx = 5y$ pass through the point $\left(\frac{1}{4},-6\right)$, we need to substitute the $x$- and $y$-coordinates of the point into the equation and solve for $k$:

\begin{align*}
-\frac{1}{2}-2k\cdot\frac{1}{4} &= 5\cdot(-6) \\
-\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{2}k &= -30 \\
-\left(1+\frac{1}{2}k\right) &= -30 \\
1+\frac{1}{2}k &= 30 \\
\frac{1}{2}k &= 29 \\
k &= \frac{29}{2}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the line $-\frac{1}{2}-2kx = 5y$ contains the point $\left(\frac{1}{4},-6\right)$ when $k = \frac{29}{2}$.
